{"title_page": "Institute of Plant Industry", "text_new": "{{Expand Russian|\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0438\u043c. \u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:Isaak square.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Behind the [[equestrian statue]] of [[Nikolai I]] near [[St Isaac's Cathedral]] is No. 4 Building of the Institute of Plant Industry]]  \n'''The Institute of Plant Industry''', '''Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry''' or '''All-Russian Research Institute of Plant Industry''' (in {{lang-ru|\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0438\u043c. \u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430}}), as it is officially called, is a research institute of [[plant genetics]], located in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]].\n\n==History==\nThe Institute of Plant Industry was established in 1921. [[Nikolai Vavilov]] was the head of this institute from 1924 to 1936 and had, and still has, the world's largest collection of plant seeds.  During the early 1930s, he became the target of the [[Lysenkoism|Lysenkoist]] debate and was exiled.  The Institute's seedbank survived the 28-month [[Siege of Leningrad]] in [[World War II]], where several botanists starved to death rather than eat the collected seeds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rensberger|first=Boyce|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-05-13/news/9202080144_1_vavilov-institute-food-crops-leningrad|title=Scientists Died Guarding Seeds During Wwii|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=May 13, 1992|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref> In 2010 the plant collection at the [[Pavlovsk Experimental Station]] was to be destroyed to make way for luxury housing.<ref>{{cite news |last= Rosenthal|first=Elisabeth|work=[[New York Times]] |title=Russia Defers Razing of Seed Repository |url=http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/10/russia-defers-razing-of-seed-repository/?ref=science |date=September 10, 2010 |accessdate=December 3, 2014|quote=A quick update on the battle to save a Russian seed bank, the Pavlovsk Research Station outside St. Petersburg: Scientists from across the globe have been appealing to President Dmitri Medvedev to rethink a government decision to allow the seed bank, home to the largest collection of European fruits and berries in the world, to be plowed away to make way for luxury homes.}}</ref> This was averted by order of President Dmitri Medvedev.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vir.nw.ru/test/vir.nw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=178:report-issued-by-the-first-channel-regarding-the-pavlovsk-experiment-station-of-vir&catid=36:news&Itemid=495&lang=en|title=Report Issued By The \u201cFirst Channel\u201d Regarding The Pavlovsk Experiment Station Of VIR - N.I.Vavilov Research Institute of Plant Industry|website=vir.nw.ru}}</ref>\n\n==Siege of Leningrad==\nThe Institute's extensive seed collection was an important target during the siege of Leningrad, Soviet officials took the time to evacuate the art from the city but neglected, or forgot to remove the world's largest seed collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/vavilov-research-institute-of-plant-industry|title=Vavilov Research Institute of Plant Industry|website=Atlas Obscura}}</ref> The scientists of the institute protected the seeds from the threats of the cold, the hungry residents of the besieged city, rats, and their own hunger. Twenty-eight of the botanists died during the siege, protecting their collection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1992-05-13-9202080144-story.html|title=SCIENTISTS DIED GUARDING SEEDS DURING WWII|first=BOYCE RENSBERGER, The Washington|last=Post|website=Sun-Sentinel.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Plant genetics]]\n* [[Lysenkoism]]\n* [[VASKhNIL]] (the All-Union Academy of Agricultural Sciences of the Soviet Union)\n* [[Pavlovsk Experimental Station]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vir.nw.ru/ Official site]\n* [http://biodiversity.ucoz.ru/index/genetic_resources_of_leguminous_plants_in_the_n_i_vavilov_institute_of_plant_industry/0-10 Genetic Resources of Leguminous Plants in the N.I. Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry]\n\n{{coord|59.9319|N|30.3086|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Research institutes in Russia]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian Academy of Agriculture Sciences]]\n[[Category:VASKhNIL]]\n[[Category:Botanical research institutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Russian|\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0438\u043c. \u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:Isaak square.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Behind the [[equestrian statue]] of [[Nikolai I]] near [[St Isaac's Cathedral]] is No. 4 Building of the Institute of Plant Industry]]  \n'''The Institute of Plant Industry''', '''Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry''' or '''All-Russian Research Institute of Plant Industry''' (in {{lang-ru|\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0438\u043c. \u041d. \u0418. \u0412\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430}}), as it is officially called, is a research institute of [[plant genetics]], located in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]].\n\n==History==\nThe Institute of Plant Industry was established in 1921. [[Nikolai Vavilov]] was the head of this institute from 1924 to 1936 and had, and still has, the world's largest collection of plant seeds.  During the early 1930s, he became the target of the [[Lysenkoism|Lysenkoist]] debate and was exiled.  The Institute's seedbank survived the 28-month [[Siege of Leningrad]] in [[World War II]], where several botanists starved to death rather than eat the collected seeds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rensberger|first=Boyce|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-05-13/news/9202080144_1_vavilov-institute-food-crops-leningrad|title=Scientists Died Guarding Seeds During Wwii|work=[[Washington Post]]|date=May 13, 1992|accessdate=December 3, 2014}}</ref> In 2010 the plant collection at the [[Pavlovsk Experimental Station]] was to be destroyed to make way for luxury housing.<ref>{{cite news |last= Rosenthal|first=Elisabeth|work=[[New York Times]] |title=Russia Defers Razing of Seed Repository |url=http://green.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/10/russia-defers-razing-of-seed-repository/?ref=science |date=September 10, 2010 |accessdate=December 3, 2014|quote=A quick update on the battle to save a Russian seed bank, the Pavlovsk Research Station outside St. Petersburg: Scientists from across the globe have been appealing to President Dmitri Medvedev to rethink a government decision to allow the seed bank, home to the largest collection of European fruits and berries in the world, to be plowed away to make way for luxury homes.}}</ref> This was averted by order of President Dmitri Medvedev.<ref>http://vir.nw.ru/test/vir.nw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=178:report-issued-by-the-first-channel-regarding-the-pavlovsk-experiment-station-of-vir&catid=36:news&Itemid=495&lang=en</ref>\n\n==Siege of Leningrad==\nThe Institute's extensive seed collection was an important target during the siege of Leningrad, Soviet officials took the time to evacuate the art from the city but neglected, or forgot to remove the world's largest seed collection.<ref>https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/vavilov-research-institute-of-plant-industry</ref> The scientists of the institute protected the seeds from the threats of the cold, the hungry residents of the besieged city, rats, and their own hunger. Twenty-eight of the botanists died during the siege, protecting their collection. <ref>https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-1992-05-13-9202080144-story.html</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Plant genetics]]\n* [[Lysenkoism]]\n* [[VASKhNIL]] (the All-Union Academy of Agricultural Sciences of the Soviet Union)\n* [[Pavlovsk Experimental Station]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vir.nw.ru/ Official site]\n* [http://biodiversity.ucoz.ru/index/genetic_resources_of_leguminous_plants_in_the_n_i_vavilov_institute_of_plant_industry/0-10 Genetic Resources of Leguminous Plants in the N.I. Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry]\n\n{{coord|59.9319|N|30.3086|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Research institutes in Russia]]\n[[Category:Research institutes in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Science and technology in Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian Academy of Agriculture Sciences]]\n[[Category:VASKhNIL]]\n[[Category:Botanical research institutes]]\n", "name_user": "Desertborn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 3 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Plant_Industry"}
